# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apostrophe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] The **16th century** begins with the Julian year 1501 (MDI) and ends with either the Julian or the Gregorian year 1600 (MDC) (depending on the reckoning used; the Gregorian calendar introduced a lapse of 10 days in October 1582).
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] The Habsburg Spanish Empire, Portuguese Empire, Ottoman Empire, Safavid Persia, Mughal India and Ming China were the most powerful and hegemonic states.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] The Renaissance in Italy and Europe saw the emergence of important artists, authors and scientists, and led to the foundation of important subjects which include accounting and political science.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] Copernicus proposed the heliocentric universe, which was met with strong resistance, and Tycho Brahe refuted the theory of celestial spheres through observational measurement of the 1572 appearance of a Milky Way supernova.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] These events directly challenged the long-held notion of an immutable universe supported by Ptolemy and Aristotle, and led to major revolutions in astronomy and science.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] Galileo Galilei became a champion of the new sciences, invented the first thermometer and made substantial contributions in the fields of physics and astronomy, becoming a major figure in the Scientific Revolution in Europe.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] Spain and Portugal colonized large parts of Central and South America, followed by France and England in Northern America and the Lesser Antilles.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] The Portuguese became the masters of trade between Brazil, the coasts of Africa, and their possessions in the Indies, whereas the Spanish came to dominate the Greater Antilles, Mexico, Peru, and opened trade across the Pacific Ocean, linking the Americas with the Indies.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] English and French privateers began to practice persistent theft of Spanish and Portuguese treasures.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] This era of colonialism established mercantilism as the leading school of economic thought, where the economic system was viewed as a zero-sum game in which any gain by one party required a loss by another.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] The mercantilist doctrine encouraged the many intra-European wars of the period and arguably fueled European expansion and imperialism throughout the world until the 19th century or early 20th century.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] The Reformation in central and northern Europe gave a major blow to the authority of the papacy and the Catholic Church.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] In England, the British-Italian Alberico Gentili wrote the first book on public international law and divided secularism from canon law and Catholic theology.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] European politics became dominated by religious conflicts, with the groundwork for the epochal Thirty Years' War being laid towards the end of the century.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] In the Middle East, the Ottoman Empire continued to expand, with the sultan taking the title of caliph, while dealing with a resurgent Persia.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] Iran and Iraq were caught by a major popularity of the Shia sect of Islam under the rule of the Safavid dynasty of warrior-mystics, providing grounds for a Persia independent of the majority-Sunni Muslim world.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] In the Indian subcontinent, following the defeat of the Delhi Sultanate and Vijayanagara Empire, new powers emerged, the Sur Empire founded by Sher Shah Suri, Deccan sultanates, Rajput states, and the Mughal Empire by Emperor Babur, a direct descendant of Timur and Genghis Khan.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] His successors Humayun and Akbar, enlarged the empire to include most of South Asia.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] Japan suffered a severe civil war at this time, known as the Sengoku period, and emerged from it as a unified nation under Toyotomi Hideyoshi.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] China was ruled by the Ming dynasty, which was becoming increasingly isolationist, coming into conflict with Japan over the control of Korea as well as Japanese pirates.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] In Africa, Christianity had begun to spread in Central Africa and Southern Africa.
[src:apostrophe/16th-century] Until the Scramble for Africa in the late 19th century, most of Africa was left uncolonized.
[src:apostrophe/a-comprehensive-grammar-of-the-english-language] The book relies on elicitation experiments as well as three corpora: a corpus from the Survey of English Usage, the Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen Corpus (UK English), and the Brown Corpus (US English).
[src:apostrophe/a-comprehensive-grammar-of-the-english-language] In 1988, Rodney Huddleston published a very critical review.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] An **abbreviation** (from Latin **brevis** 'short') is a shortened form of a word or phrase, by any method including shortening, contraction, initialism (which includes acronym), or crasis.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] An abbreviation may be a shortened form of a word, usually ended with a trailing full stop (period).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For example, the term *etc.* is the usual abbreviation for the Latin phrase *et cetera*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] A *contraction* is an abbreviation formed by leaving out letters or sounds, typically replaced by an apostrophe in English.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Examples include *I'm* for *I am* and *li'l* for *little*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] An *initialism* or *acronym* is an abbreviation consisting of the initial letter of a sequence of words without other punctuation.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For example, FBI (/ˌɛf.biːˈaɪ/), USA (/ˌjuː.ɛsˈeɪ/), IBM (/ˌaɪ.biːˈɛm/), BBC (/ˌbiː.biːˈsiː/).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] When initialism is used as the preferred term, acronym refers more specifically to when the abbreviation is pronounced as a word rather than as separate letters; examples include SWAT and NASA.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Initialisms, contractions and crasis share some semantic and phonetic functions, and are connected by the term *abbreviation* in loose parlance.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In early times, abbreviations may have been common due to the effort involved in writing (many inscriptions were carved in stone) or to provide secrecy via obfuscation.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Reduction of a word to a single letter was common in both Greek and Roman writing.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In Roman inscriptions, "Words were commonly abbreviated by using the initial letter or letters of words, and most inscriptions have at least one abbreviation".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] However, "some could have more than one meaning, depending on their context.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Abbreviations were frequently used in early English.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Manuscripts of copies of the Old English poem *Beowulf* used many abbreviations, for example the Tironian et (⁊) or & for *and*, and y for *since*, so that "not much space is wasted".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The standardisation of English in the 15th through 17th centuries included a growth in the use of such abbreviations.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] At first, abbreviations were sometimes represented with various suspension signs, not only periods.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For example, sequences like ⟨er⟩ were replaced with ⟨ɔ⟩, as in mastɔ for *master* and exacɔbate for *exacerbate*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] While this may seem trivial, it was symptomatic of an attempt by people manually reproducing academic texts to reduce the copy time.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] — Warden of Merton College, University of Oxford in *Registrum Annalium Collegii Mertonensis*, 1503.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In the Early Modern English period, between the 15th and 17th centuries, the thorn Þ was used for *th*, as in Þe ('the').
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In modern times, ⟨Þ⟩ was often used (in the form ⟨y⟩) for promotional reasons, as in Ye Olde Tea Shoppe.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] During the growth of philological linguistic theory in academic Britain, abbreviating became very fashionable.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Likewise, a century earlier in Boston, a fad of abbreviation started that swept the United States, with the globally popular term OK generally credited as a remnant of its influence.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Over the years, however, the lack of convention in some style guides has made it difficult to determine which two-word abbreviations should be abbreviated with periods and which should not.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Widespread use of electronic communication through mobile phones and the Internet during the 1990s led to a marked rise in colloquial abbreviation.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] This was due largely to increasing popularity of textual communication services such as instant and text messaging.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The original SMS supported message lengths of 160 characters at most (using the GSM 03.38 character set), for instance.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] This brevity gave rise to an informal abbreviation scheme sometimes called Textese, with which 10% or more of the words in a typical SMS message are abbreviated.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] More recently Twitter, a popular social networking service, began driving abbreviation use with 140 character message limits.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In HTML, abbreviations can be annotated using a dedicated tag: `<abbr title="Editor">Ed.</abbr>` In this example, the meaning of "Ed." as "Editor" is revealed by hovering the cursor over it.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In modern English, there are multiple conventions for abbreviation, and there is controversy as to which should be used.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] One generally accepted rule is to be consistent in a body of work.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] To this end, publishers may express their preferences in a style guide.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Some controversies that arise are described below.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] If the original word was capitalized then the first letter of its abbreviation should retain the capital, for example Lev. for *Leviticus*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] When a word is abbreviated to more than a single letter and was originally spelled with lower case letters then there is no need for capitalization.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] However, when abbreviating a phrase where only the first letter of each word is taken, then all letters should be capitalized, as in YTD for *year-to-date*, PCB for *printed circuit board* and FYI for *for your information*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] However, see the following section regarding abbreviations that have become common vocabulary: these are no longer written with capital letters.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] A period (full stop) is sometimes used to signify abbreviation, but opinion is divided as to when and if this convention is best practice.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] According to Hart's Rules, a word shortened by dropping letters from the end terminates with a full stop (period), whereas a word shorted by dropping letters from the middle does not.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Fowler's Modern English Usage says a full stop (period) is used for both of these shortened forms, but recommends against this practice.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] It advises it only for end-shortened words and lower-case initialisms, not for middle-shortened words and upper-case initialisms.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Some British style guides, such as for The Guardian and The Economist, disallow periods for all abbreviations.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In American English, the period is usually included regardless of whether or not it is a contraction, e.g.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] *Dr.* or *Mrs.* In some cases, periods are optional, as in either *US* or *U.S.* for *United States*, *EU* or *E.U.* for *European Union*, and *UN* or *U.N.* for *United Nations*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] There are some house styles, however—American ones included—that remove the periods from almost all abbreviations.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Acronyms that were originally capitalized (with or without periods) but have since entered the vocabulary as generic words are no longer written with capital letters nor with any periods.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Examples are sonar, radar, lidar, laser, snafu, and scuba.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In the past, some initialisms were styled with a period after each letter and a space between each pair.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] There are multiple ways to pluralize an abbreviation.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Sometimes this accomplished by adding an apostrophe and an *s* ('s), as in "two PC's have broken screens".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] But, some find this confusing since the notation can indicate possessive case.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] And, this style is deprecated by many style guides.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For instance, Kate Turabian, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For example, "DVDs" and "URLs" and "Ph.D.'s", while the Modern Language Association explicitly says, "do not use an apostrophe to form the plural of an abbreviation".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Also, the American Psychological Association specifically says, "without an apostrophe".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] However, the 1999 style guide for *The New York Times* states that the addition of an apostrophe is necessary when pluralizing all abbreviations, preferring "PC's, TV's and VCR's".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Forming a plural of an initialization without an apostrophe can also be used for a number, or a letter.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For units of measure, the same form is used for both singular and plural.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] When an abbreviation contains more than one period, *Hart's Rules* recommends putting the *s* after the final one.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] According to *Hart's Rules*, an apostrophe may be used in rare cases where clarity calls for it, for example when letters or symbols are referred to as objects.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In Latin, and continuing to the derivative forms in European languages as well as English, single-letter abbreviations had the plural being a doubling of the letter for note-taking.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Most of these deal with writing and publishing.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] A few longer abbreviations use this as well.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Publications based in the U.S. tend to follow the style guides of *The Chicago Manual of Style* and the Associated Press.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The U.S. government follows a style guide published by the U.S.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The National Institute of Standards and Technology sets the style for abbreviations of units.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Writers often use shorthand to denote units of measure.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Such shorthand can be an abbreviation, such as "in" for "inch" or can be a symbol such as "km" for "kilometre".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In the International System of Units (SI) manual the word "symbol" is used consistently to define the shorthand used to represent the various SI units of measure.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] A syllabic abbreviation is usually formed from the initial syllables of several words, such as *Interpol* = *International* + *police*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are usually written using lower case, sometimes starting with a capital letter, and are always pronounced as words rather than letter by letter.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations should be distinguished from portmanteaus, which combine two words without necessarily taking whole syllables from each.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not widely used in English.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Some UK government agencies such as Ofcom (Office of Communications) and the former Oftel (Office of Telecommunications) use this style.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] New York City has various neighborhoods named by syllabic abbreviation, such as Tribeca (Triangle below Canal Street) and SoHo (South of Houston Street).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] This usage has spread into other American cities, giving SoMa, San Francisco (South of Market), and LoDo, Denver (Lower Downtown), amongst others.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Sections of California are also often colloquially syllabically abbreviated, as in NorCal (Northern California), CenCal (Central California), and SoCal (Southern California).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Additionally, in the context of Los Angeles, the syllabic abbreviation SoHo (Southern Hollywood) refers to the southern portion of the Hollywood neighborhood.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Partially syllabic abbreviations are preferred by the US Navy, as they increase readability amidst the large number of initialisms that would otherwise have to fit into the same acronyms.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Hence *DESRON 6* is used (in the full capital form) to mean "Destroyer Squadron 6", while *COMNAVAIRLANT* would be "Commander, Naval Air Force (in the) Atlantic".
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are a prominent feature of Newspeak, the fictional language of George Orwell's dystopian novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The political contractions of Newspeak—*Ingsoc* (English Socialism), *Minitrue* (Ministry of Truth), *Miniplenty* (Ministry of Plenty)—are described by Orwell as similar to real examples of German *(see below)* and Russian (*see below)* contractions in the 20th century.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The contractions in Newspeak are supposed to have a political function by virtue of their abbreviated structure itself: nice sounding and easily pronounceable, their purpose is to mask all ideological content from the speaker.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] A more recent syllabic abbreviation has emerged with the disease COVID-19 (Corona Virus Disease 2019) caused by the Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (itself frequently abbreviated to SARS-CoV-2, partly an initialism).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In Albanian, syllabic acronyms are sometimes used for composing a person's name, such as *Migjeni*—an abbreviation from his original name (*Millosh Gjergj Nikolla*) a famous Albanian poet and writer—or *ASDRENI* (*Aleksander Stavre Drenova*), another famous Albanian poet.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Other such names which are used commonly in recent decades are GETOAR, composed from *Gegeria* + *Tosks* (representing the two main dialects of the Albanian language, Gegë and Toskë), and *Arbanon*—which is an alternative way used to describe all Albanian lands.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations were and are common in German; much like acronyms in English, they have a distinctly modern connotation, although contrary to popular belief, many date back to before 1933, if not the end of the Great War.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] *Kriminalpolizei*, literally *criminal police* but idiomatically the Criminal Investigation Department of any German police force, begat *KriPo* (variously capitalised), and likewise *Schutzpolizei* (*protection police* or *uniform department*) begat *SchuPo*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Along the same lines, the Swiss Federal Railways' Transit Police—the *Transportpolizei*—are abbreviated as the *TraPo*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] With the National Socialist German Workers' Party gaining power came a frenzy of government reorganisation, and with it a series of entirely new syllabic abbreviations.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Non regime-aligned partially syllabic abbreviations also existed like "Gröfaz" for the self-proclaimed "größter Feldherr aller Zeiten" (greatest military commander of all time), i.e.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The new order of the German Democratic Republic in the east brought about a conscious denazification, but also a repudiation of earlier turns of phrase in favour of neologisms such as *Stasi* for *Staatssicherheit* ("state security", the secret police) and *VoPo* for *Volkspolizei*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The phrase *politisches Büro*, which may be rendered literally as "office of politics" or idiomatically as "political party steering committee", became *Politbüro*.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not only used in politics, however.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are very common in Russian, Belarusian and Ukrainian.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] They are often used as names of organizations.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Historically, popularization of abbreviations was a way to simplify mass-education in 1920s (see Likbez).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The word *kolkhoz* (*kollektívnoye khozyáystvo*, collective farm) is another example.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Leninist organisations such as the *Comintern* (*Communist International*) and *Komsomol* (*Kommunisticheskii Soyuz Molodyozhi*, or "Communist youth union") used Russian language syllabic abbreviations.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In the modern Russian language, words like *Rosselkhozbank* (from Rossiysky selskokhozyaystvenny bank — Russian Agricultural Bank, RusAg) and *Minobrnauki* (from Ministerstvo obrazovaniya i nauki — Ministry of Education and Science) are still commonly used.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] In nearby Belarus, there are *Beltelecom* (Belarus Telecommunication) and Belsat (Belarus Satellite).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are common in Spanish; examples abound in organization names such as Pemex for *Petróleos Mexicanos* ("Mexican Petroleums") or Fonafifo for *Fondo Nacional de Financimiento Forestal* (National Forestry Financing Fund).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] ("Banamex"), Teléfonos de México, S.A.B. de C.V.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] ("TELMEX"), Operadora de Cinemas, S.A. de C.V.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Malaysian abbreviation often uses letters from each word, while Indonesia usually uses syllables; although some cases do not follow the style.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For example, general elections in Malaysian Malay often shortened into PRU (**p**ilihan **r**aya **u**mum) while Indonesian often shortened into pemilu (**pemil**ihan **u**mum).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Another example is Ministry of Health in which Malaysian Malay uses KKM (**K**ementerian **K**esihatan **M**alaysia), compared to Indonesian Kemenkes (**Kemen**terian **Kes**ehatan).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] East Asian languages whose writing systems use Chinese characters form abbreviations similarly by using key Chinese characters from a term or phrase.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] For example, in Japanese the term for the United Nations, *kokusai rengō* (国際連合) is often abbreviated to *kokuren* (国連).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] (Such abbreviations are called ryakugo (略語) in Japanese; see also Japanese abbreviated and contracted words).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The syllabic abbreviation of kanji words is frequently used for universities: for instance, *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō daigaku* (東京大学, University of Tokyo) and is used similarly in Chinese: *Běidà* (北大) for *Běijīng Dàxué* (北京大学, Peking University).
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] Korean universities often follow the same conventions, such as *Hongdae* (홍대) as short for *Hongik Daehakgyo*, or Hongik University.
[src:apostrophe/abbreviation] The English phrase "Gung ho" originated as a Chinese abbreviation.
[src:apostrophe/alif] These letters are believed to have derived from an Egyptian hieroglyph depicting the head of an ox to describe the initial sound of **ʾalp*, the West Semitic word for "ox" (compare Biblical Hebrew אֶלֶף *ʾelef*, 'ox').
[src:apostrophe/alif] The Phoenician variant gave rise to the Greek alpha (Α), being reinterpreted to express not the glottal consonant but the accompanying vowel, and hence the Latin A and Cyrillic А and possibly the Armenian letter Ա.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Phonetically, *aleph* originally represented the onset of a vowel at the glottis.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Semitic languages, this functions as a prosthetic weak consonant, allowing roots with only two true consonants to be conjugated in the manner of a standard three consonant Semitic root.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In most Hebrew dialects as well as Syriac, the *aleph* is an absence of a true consonant, a glottal stop ([ʔ]), the sound found in the catch in *uh**-**oh*.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Arabic, the *alif* represents the glottal stop pronunciation when it is the initial letter of a word.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In texts with diacritical marks, the pronunciation of an *aleph* as a consonant is rarely indicated by a special marking, hamza in Arabic and mappiq in Tiberian Hebrew.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In later Semitic languages, *aleph* could sometimes function as a *mater lectionis* indicating the presence of a vowel elsewhere (usually long).
[src:apostrophe/alif] When this practice began is the subject of some controversy, though it had become well established by the late stage of Old Aramaic (ca.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Aleph is often transliterated as U+02BE ʾ MODIFIER LETTER RIGHT HALF RING, based on the Greek *spiritus lenis* *ʼ*; for example, in the transliteration of the letter name itself, **ʾāleph**.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The name *aleph* is derived from the West Semitic word for 'ox', as in the Biblical Hebrew word *eleph* (אֶלֶף) 'ox', and the shape of the letter derives from a Proto-Sinaitic glyph that may have been based on an Egyptian hieroglyph, which depicts an ox's head.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Modern Standard Arabic, the word أليف /ʔaliːf/ literally means 'tamed' or 'familiar', derived from the root ʔ-L-F, from which the verb ألِف /ʔalifa/ means 'to be acquainted with; to be on intimate terms with'.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In modern Hebrew, the same root ʔ-L-P (alef-lamed-peh) gives *me'ulaf*, the passive participle of the verb *le'alef*, meaning 'trained' (when referring to pets) or 'tamed' (when referring to wild animals).
[src:apostrophe/alif] The Egyptian "vulture" hieroglyph (Gardiner G1), by convention pronounced [a]) is also referred to as *aleph*, on grounds that it has traditionally been taken to represent a glottal stop ([ʔ]), although some recent suggestions tend towards an alveolar approximant ([ɹ]) sound instead.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Despite the name it does not correspond to an aleph in cognate Semitic words, where the single "reed" hieroglyph is found instead.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The phoneme is commonly transliterated by a symbol composed of two half-rings, in Unicode (as of version 5.1, in the Latin Extended-D range) encoded at U+A722 Ꜣ LATIN CAPITAL LETTER EGYPTOLOGICAL ALEF and U+A723 ꜣ LATIN SMALL LETTER EGYPTOLOGICAL ALEF.
[src:apostrophe/alif] A fallback representation is the numeral *3*, or the Middle English character *ȝ* Yogh; neither are to be preferred to the genuine Egyptological characters.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Written as ا or 𐪑, spelled as ألف or 𐪑𐪁𐪐 and transliterated as **alif**, it is the first letter in Arabic and North Arabian.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Together with Hebrew aleph, Greek alpha and Latin A, it is descended from Phoenician *ʾāleph*, from a reconstructed Proto-Canaanite **ʾalp** "ox".
[src:apostrophe/alif] In classical Arabic calligraphy, *alif* is also used as the main reference for the proportions of the other letters.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Its height is traditionally measured in *nuqṭah* (نقطة "dots"), which represent the width of the pen nib.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Different calligraphy manuals give different values for the height of *alif*, usually between five and ten dots, depending on the script.
[src:apostrophe/alif] A 2020 study by Yaghan analyzed these traditional rules using geometric methods and showed that the different historical measurements can be explained by changes in pen angle and how the dots are arranged, while still keeping simple whole-number height-to-width ratios.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The study also discusses how other letters were historically derived from *alif* and from a circle based on its height.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Alif has the highest frequency out of all 28 letters in the Arabic abjad.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The Arabic letter alif was originally used to render either a long /aː/ or a glottal stop /ʔ/.
[src:apostrophe/alif] That led to orthographical confusion and to the introduction of the additional marking **hamzat qaṭ'** ﺀ to fix the problem.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Hamza is not considered a full letter in Arabic orthography: in most cases, it appears on a carrier, either a **wāw** (ؤ), a dotless **yā'** (ئ), or an alif.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The choice of carrier depends on complicated orthographic rules.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Alif إ أ is generally the carrier if the only adjacent vowel is **fatḥah**.
[src:apostrophe/alif] It is the only possible carrier if hamza is the first phoneme of a word.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Where alif acts as a carrier for hamza, hamza is added above the alif, or, for initial alif-**kasrah**, below it and indicates that the letter so modified is indeed a glottal stop, not a long vowel.
[src:apostrophe/alif] A second type of hamza, **hamzat waṣl** (همزة وصل), whose diacritic is normally omitted outside of sacred texts, occurs only as the initial letter of the definite article and in some related cases.
[src:apostrophe/alif] It differs from **hamzat qaṭ'** in that it is elided after a preceding vowel.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The *alif mamdūda* is a double alif, expressing a glottal stop /ʔ/ followed by a long /aː/.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Essentially, it is the same as a أا sequence, but is represented by placing a *maddah* over a regular alif: آ (final ـآ) *'ā* /ʔaː/, for example in آخر **ākhir** /ʔaːxir/ 'last'.
[src:apostrophe/alif] "It has become standard for a *hamza* followed by a long ā to be written as two *alifs*, one vertical and one horizontal", the "horizontal" alif being the *maddah* sign.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The **ى** ('limited/restricted alif', **alif maqṣūrah**), commonly known in Egypt as **alif layyinah** (ألف لينة, 'flexible alif'), may appear only at the end of a word.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Although it looks different from a regular *alif*, it represents the same sound /aː/, often realized as a short vowel.
[src:apostrophe/alif] When it is written, **alif maqṣūrah** is indistinguishable from final Persian *ye* or Arabic **yā'** as it is written in the Nile valley, sometimes elsewhere, and in the Quran.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The letter is transliterated as *y* in Kazakh, representing the vowel /ə/.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Jawi it is known as *ye* and represents a schwa /ə/.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Arabic, *alif maqsurah* ى is not used initially or medially, and it is not joinable initially or medially in any font.
[src:apostrophe/alif] However, the letter is used initially and medially in the Uyghur Arabic alphabet and the Arabic-based Kyrgyz alphabet, representing the vowel /ɯ/: (ىـ ـىـ‎).
[src:apostrophe/alif] As a vowel, the letter *alif maqsurah* can be a carrier with a hamza.
[src:apostrophe/alif] As a numeral, alif stands for the number one.
[src:apostrophe/alif] It may be modified as follows to represent other numbers.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The Aramaic reflex of the letter is conventionally represented with the Hebrew א in typography for convenience, but the actual graphic form varied significantly over the long history and wide geographic extent of the language.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Modern Israeli Hebrew, the letter either represents a glottal stop ([ʔ]) or indicates a hiatus (the separation of two adjacent vowels into distinct syllables, with no intervening consonant).
[src:apostrophe/alif] It is sometimes silent (word-finally always, word-medially sometimes: הוּא‎ [hu] "he", רָאשִׁי‎ [ʁaˈʃi] "main", רֹאשׁ‎ [ʁoʃ] "head", רִאשׁוֹן‎ [ʁiˈʃon] "first").
[src:apostrophe/alif] The pronunciation varies in different Jewish ethnic divisions.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In gematria, aleph represents the number 1, and when used at the beginning of Hebrew years, it means 1000 (e.g. א׳תשנ״ד‎ in numbers would be the Hebrew date 1754, not to be confused with 1754 CE).
[src:apostrophe/alif] Aleph, along with ayin, resh, he and heth, cannot receive a dagesh.
[src:apostrophe/alif] (However, there are few very rare examples of the Masoretes adding a dagesh or mappiq to an aleph or resh.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Modern Hebrew, the frequency of the usage of alef, out of all the letters, is 4.94%.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Aleph is sometimes used as a mater lectionis to denote a vowel, usually /a/.
[src:apostrophe/alif] That use is more common in words of Aramaic and Arabic origin, in foreign names, and some other borrowed words.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Aleph is the subject of a midrash that praises its humility in not demanding to start the Bible.
[src:apostrophe/alif] (In Hebrew, the Bible begins with the second letter of the alphabet, bet.) In the story, aleph is rewarded by being allowed to start the Ten Commandments.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In the Sefer Yetzirah, the letter aleph is king over breath, formed air in the universe, temperate in the year, and the chest in the soul.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Aleph is also the first letter of the Hebrew word *emet* (אֱמֶת‎), which means *truth*.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In Judaism, it was the letter aleph that was carved into the head of the golem that ultimately gave it life.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Aleph also begins the three words that make up God's name in Exodus, I Am who I Am (in Hebrew, Ehyeh Asher Ehyeh אהיה אשר אהיה), and aleph is an important part of mystical amulets and formulas.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The letter can be seen as being composed of an upper yud, a lower yud, and a vav leaning on a diagonal.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The upper yud represents the hidden and ineffable aspects of God while the lower yud represents God's revelation and presence in the world.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The vav ("hook") connects the two realms.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Loanwords from Hebrew or Aramaic in Yiddish are spelled as they are in their language of origin.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In the Syriac alphabet, the first letter is ܐ, Classical Syriac: ܐܵܠܲܦ, alap (in eastern dialects) or olaph (in western dialects).
[src:apostrophe/alif] It is used in word-initial position to mark a word beginning with a vowel, but some words beginning with *i* or *u* do not need its help, and sometimes, an initial alap/olaph is elided.
[src:apostrophe/alif] For example, when the Syriac first-person singular pronoun ܐܸܢܵܐ is in enclitic positions, it is pronounced *no/na* (again west/east), rather than the full form *eno/ana*.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The letter occurs very regularly at the end of words, where it represents the long final vowels *o/a* or *e*.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In the middle of the word, the letter represents either a glottal stop between vowels (but West Syriac pronunciation often makes it a palatal approximant), a long *i/e* (less commonly *o/a*) or is silent.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In the Ancient South Arabian alphabet, 𐩱 appears as the seventeenth letter of the South Arabian abjad.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The letter is used to render a glottal stop /ʔ/.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In the Ge'ez alphabet, ʾälef አ appears as the thirteenth letter of its abjad.
[src:apostrophe/alif] This letter is also used to render a glottal stop /ʔ/.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In set theory, the Hebrew aleph glyph is used as the symbol to denote the aleph numbers, which represent the cardinality of infinite sets.
[src:apostrophe/alif] This notation was introduced by mathematician Georg Cantor.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In older mathematics books, the letter aleph is often printed upside down by accident, partly because a Monotype matrix for aleph was mistakenly constructed the wrong way up.
[src:apostrophe/alif] The Mapai political party in Israel used an aleph as its election symbol, and featured it prominently in its campaign posters.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Guru Nanak, regarded as the founder of Sikhism, used the aleph to represent the oneness of God.
[src:apostrophe/alif] Aleph is also the current name of a religious cult in Japan.
[src:apostrophe/alif] In IPA the aleph glotal plosive is depicted by Ɂ (unicode point LATIN CAPITAL LETTER GLOTAL STOP, U+0241) In earlier days of phonology a small arch based on Greek Smooth breathing or a doubled one (now depicted by Ꜣ, unicode point LATIN CAPITAL LETTER EGYPTOLOGICAL ALEF) was used for this purpose.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The APA became involved in journal publishing in 1923.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] In 1929, an APA committee had a seven-page writer's guide published in the *Psychological Bulletin*.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] In 1944, a 32-page guide appeared as an article in the same journal.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The first edition of the *APA Publication Manual* was published in 1952 as a 61-page supplement to the *Psychological Bulletin*, marking the beginning of a recognized "APA style".
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The initial edition went through two revisions: one in 1957, and one in 1967.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The increasing length of the guidelines and its transformation into a manual have been accompanied by increasingly explicit prescriptions about many aspects of acceptable work.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The earliest editions were controlled by a group of field leaders who were behaviorist in orientation and the manual has continued to foster that ideology, even as it has influenced many other fields.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] According to the American Psychological Association, APA format can make the point of an argument clear and simple to the reader.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] Particularly influential were the "Guidelines for Nonsexist Language in APA Journals", first published as a modification to the 1974 edition, which provided practical alternatives to sexist language then in common usage.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The guidelines for reducing bias in language have been updated over the years and presently provide practical guidance for writing about age, disability, gender, participation in research, race and ethnicity, sexual orientation, socioeconomic status, and intersectionality (APA, 2020, Chapter 5).
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The seventh edition of the *Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association* is the current one, published in October 2019.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The goal of the book is to help people become better writers and communicators by promoting clarity, precision, and inclusivity.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The manual has new resources for students, including a student title page, student paper formats, and student-related reference formats such as classroom course pack material and classroom website sources.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The book also includes new journal article reporting standards for qualitative and mixed methods research in addition to updated standards for quantitative research.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The bias-free language guidelines have also been updated to reflect current best practices for talking about people's personal characteristics.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The manual addresses accessibility for people with disabilities for the first time.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] APA worked with accessibility experts to ensure APA style is accessible.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] For example, the in-text citation format is shortened so that the citations are easier to read for people who, for example, use screen readers or have cognitive disabilities.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] Running heads are used in papers that follow APA Style.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The running head is an abbreviated version of the paper title that is included in the header of professional papers along with the page number.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] In student papers, the page number is placed in the header but the page title is not, unless otherwise stated by the course instructor or educational institution.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The manual has hundreds of reference examples, including formats for audiovisual media, social media, and webpages.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] There are many sample tables and figures, including basic student-friendly examples such as bar graphs.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] There are also sample papers for professionals and students.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] Since the seventh edition, APA also provides an APA Style website and APA Style blog to help people with APA style and answer common questions.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The sixth edition of the *Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association* was in effect from 2009 to 2019, after four years of development.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] To accomplish these revisions, the Task Force appointed working groups of four to nine members in seven areas: bias-free language, ethics, graphics, Journal Article Reporting Standards, references, statistics, and writing style (APA, 2009, pp. xvii–xviii).
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The APA explained the issuing of a new edition only eight years after the fifth edition by pointing to the increased use of online source or online access to academic journals (6th edition, p.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] The sixth edition is accompanied by a style website as well as the APA Style Blog which answers many common questions from users.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] Sample papers in the first printing of the sixth edition contained errors.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] APA staff posted all of the corrections online for free in a single document on October 1, 2009, and shortly thereafter alerted users to the existence of the corrections in an APA blog entry.
[src:apostrophe/apa-style] All copies of the printing with errors were soon after recalled in 2009 (including those from major retailers such as Amazon.com) and a new printing correcting all the errors, with a copyright date of 2010, was issued.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The **apostrophe** (**’**, **'**) is a punctuation mark and sometimes a diacritical mark in languages that use the Latin alphabet and some other writing systems.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] It is also used in a few exceptional cases for the marking of plurals, e.g., "p's and q's" or Oakland A's.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The same mark is used as a single quotation mark.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] It is also substituted informally for other marks – for example instead of the prime symbol to indicate the units of foot or minutes of arc.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The word *apostrophe* comes from the Greek ἡ ἀπόστροφος [προσῳδία] (*hē apóstrophos [prosōidía]*, '[the accent of] turning away or elision'), through Latin and French.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The apostrophe was first used by Pietro Bembo in his edition of *De Aetna* (1496).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] It was introduced into English in the 16th century in imitation of French practice.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Introduced by Geoffroy Tory (1529), the apostrophe was used in place of a vowel letter to indicate elision (as in *l'heure* in place of *la heure*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] It was also frequently used in place of a final ⟨e⟩ (which was still pronounced at the time) when it was elided before a vowel, as in *un' heure*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Modern French orthography has restored the spelling *une heure*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] From the 16th century, following French practice, the apostrophe was used when a vowel letter was omitted either because of incidental elision ("I'm" for "I am") or because the letter no longer represented a sound ("lov'd" for "loved").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] English spelling retained many inflections that were not pronounced as syllables, notably verb endings ("-est", "-eth", "-es", "-ed") and the noun ending "-es", which marked either plurals or possessives, also known as genitives .
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The use of elision has continued to the present day, but significant changes have been made to the possessive and plural uses.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] By the 18th century, an apostrophe with the addition of an ⟨s⟩ was regularly used for all possessive singular forms, even when the letter ⟨e⟩ was not omitted (as in "the gate's height").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] This was regarded as representing not the elision of the ⟨e⟩ in the "-e" or "-es" ending of the word being pluralized, but the elision of the ⟨e⟩ from the Old English genitive singular inflection "-es".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The plural genitive did not use the "-es" inflection, and since many plural forms already consisted of the "-s" or "-es" ending, using the apostrophe in place of the elisioned ⟨e⟩ could lead to singular and plural possessives of a given word having the exact same spelling.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The solution was to use an apostrophe after the plural ⟨s⟩ (as in "girls' dresses"); however, this was not universally accepted until the mid-19th century.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Plurals not ending in -s keep the -'s marker, such as "children's toys, the men's toilet", since there was no risk of ambiguity.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The apostrophe is used in English to indicate what is, for historical reasons, misleadingly called the possessive case in the English language.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] This case was called the genitive until the 18th century and, like the genitive case in other languages, expresses relationships other than possession.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For example, in the expressions "the school's headmaster", "the men's department", and "tomorrow's weather", the school does not own/possess the headmaster, men do not own/possess the department, and tomorrow does not/will not own the weather.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] That dictionary also cites a study, which found that only 40% of the possessive forms were used to indicate actual possession.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The modern spelling convention distinguishes possessive singular forms ("Bernadette's", "flower's", "glass's", "one's") from simple plural forms ("Bernadettes", "flowers", "glasses", "ones"), and both of those from possessive plural forms ("Bernadettes'", "flowers'", "glasses'", "ones'").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For example, the word "glass's" is the singular possessive form of the noun "glass".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The plural form of "glass" is "glasses" and the plural possessive form is, therefore, "glasses'".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] One would therefore say "I drank the glass's contents" to indicate drinking from one glass, but "I drank the glasses' contents" after also drinking from another glass.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For singular forms, the modern possessive or genitive inflection is a survival from certain genitive inflections in Old English, for which the apostrophe originally marked the loss of the old ⟨e⟩ (for example, *lambes* became *lamb's*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Its use for indicating plural "possessive" forms was not standard before the middle of the 19th century.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For most singular nouns, the ending "'s" is added; e.g., "the cat's whiskers".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] When the noun is a normal plural, with an added ⟨s⟩, no extra ⟨s⟩ is added in the possessive, and it is pronounced accordingly; so "the neighbours' garden" (there is more than one neighbour owning the garden) is standard rather than "the neighbours's garden".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Compound nouns have their singular possessives formed with an apostrophe and an added ⟨s⟩, in accordance with the given rules: *the Attorney-General's husband*; *the Lord Warden of the Cinque Ports's prerogative*; *this Minister for Justice's intervention*; *her father-in-law's new wife*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some grammars make no distinction in meaning between the two forms.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some publishers' style guides make a distinction, assigning the "segregatory" (or "distributive") meaning to the form "John's and Mary's" and the "combinatorial" (or "joint") meaning to the form "John and Mary's".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] A third alternative is a construction of the form "Jack's children and Jill's", which is always distributive, i.e. it designates the combined set of Jack's children and Jill's children.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] When a coordinate possessive construction has two personal pronouns, the normal possessive inflection is used, and there is no apostrophe (e.g., "his and her children").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The issue of the use of the apostrophe arises when the coordinate construction includes a noun (phrase) and a pronoun.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In this case, the inflection of only the last item may sometimes be, at least marginally, acceptable ("you and your spouse's bank account").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The inflection of both is normally preferred (e.g.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Jack's and your dogs), but there is a tendency to avoid this construction, too, in favour of a construction that does not use a coordinate possessive (e.g. by using "Jack's letters and yours").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Where a construction like "Jack's and your dogs" is used, the interpretation is usually "segregatory" (i.e. not joint possession).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] If the word or compound includes, or ends with, a punctuation mark, an apostrophe and an ⟨s⟩ are still added in the usual way: "Westward Ho!'s railway station"; "*Awaye!*'s Paulette Whitten recorded Bob Wilson's story"; *Washington, D.C.'s museums*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] (assuming that the prevailing style requires full stops in *D.C.*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] An apostrophe is used in time and money references in constructions such as *one hour's respite*, *two weeks' holiday*, *a dollar's worth*, *five pounds' worth*, *one mile's drive from here*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] This is like an ordinary possessive use.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For example, *one hour's respite* means *a respite of one hour* (exactly as *the cat's whiskers* means *the whiskers of the cat*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] No apostrophe is used in the following possessive pronouns and adjectives: *hers*, *his*, *its*, *my*, *mine*, *ours*, *theirs*, *whose*, and *yours*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] All other possessive pronouns do end with an apostrophe and an ⟨s⟩.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In singular forms, the apostrophe comes first, e.g.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] *one's*; *everyone's*; *somebody's*, *nobody else's*, etc., while the apostrophe follows the ⟨s⟩ in plural forms as with nouns: *the others' complaints*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The possessive of *it* was originally *it's*, in contrast to the modern *its*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The apostrophe was dropped by the early 19th century.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Authorities are now unanimous that *it's* can be only a contraction of *it is* or *it has*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Despite this, using *it's* as a possessive pronoun is a common grammatical error in present times.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some singular nouns are pronounced with a sibilant sound at the end: /s/ or /z/.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Most respected authorities recommend that practically all singular nouns, including those ending with a sibilant sound, have possessive forms with an extra ⟨s⟩ after the apostrophe so that the spelling reflects the underlying pronunciation.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Examples include Oxford University Press, the Modern Language Association, the BBC and *The Economist*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Such authorities demand possessive singulars like these: *Bridget Jones's Diary*; *Tony Adams's friend; my boss's job; the US's economy*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Although less common, some contemporary writers still follow the older practice of omitting the second *'s* in some cases ending with a sibilant, but usually not when written *-x* or *-xe*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The Associated Press Stylebook recommends or allows the practice of omitting the additional ⟨s⟩ in proper nouns ending with an ⟨s⟩, but not in words ending with other sibilants (⟨z⟩ and ⟨x⟩).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Similar examples of notable names ending in an ⟨s⟩ that are often given a possessive apostrophe with no additional ⟨s⟩ include *Dickens* and *Williams*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some writers like to reflect standard spoken practice in cases like these with *sake*: *for convenience' sake*, *for goodness' sake*, *for appearance' sake*, *for compromise' sake*, etc.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] This punctuation is preferred in major style guides.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Others prefer to add *'s*: *for convenience's sake*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Still others prefer to omit the apostrophe when there is an ⟨s⟩ sound before *sake*: *for morality's sake*, but *for convenience sake*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The English possessive of French nouns ending in a silent ⟨s⟩, ⟨x⟩, or ⟨z⟩ is addressed by various style guides.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Certainly a sibilant is pronounced in examples like *Descartes's* and *Dumas's*; the question addressed here is whether ⟨s⟩ needs to be added.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The same principles and residual uncertainties apply with "naturalised" English words, like *Illinois* and *Arkansas*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For possessive *plurals* of words ending in a silent ⟨x⟩, ⟨z⟩ or ⟨s⟩, the few authorities that address the issue at all typically call for an added ⟨s⟩ and suggest that the apostrophe precede the ⟨s⟩: *The Loucheux's homeland is in the Yukon*; *Compare the two Dumas's literary achievements*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The possessive of a cited French title with a silent plural ending is uncertain: "*Trois femmes*'s long and complicated publication history", but "*Les noces*' singular effect was 'exotic primitive' ..." (with nearby sibilants *-ce-* in *noces* and *s-* in *singular*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Guides typically seek a principle that will yield uniformity, even for foreign words that fit awkwardly with standard English punctuation.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Place names in the United States do not use the possessive apostrophe on federal maps and signs.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The United States Board on Geographic Names, which has responsibility for formal naming of municipalities and geographic features, has deprecated the use of possessive apostrophes since 1890 so as not to show ownership of the place.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Only five names of natural features in the US are officially spelled with a genitive apostrophe: Martha's Vineyard; Ike's Point, New Jersey; John E's Pond, Rhode Island; Carlos Elmer's Joshua View, Arizona; and Clark's Mountain, Oregon.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some municipalities, originally incorporated using the apostrophe, have dropped it in accordance with this policy; Taylors Falls in Minnesota, for example, was originally incorporated as "Taylor's Falls".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] On the state level, the federal policy is not always followed: Vermont's official state website has a page on Camel's Hump State Forest.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Australia's Intergovernmental Committee on Surveying and Mapping also has a no-apostrophe policy, a practice it says goes back to the 1900s and which is generally followed around the country.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] On the other hand, the United Kingdom has Bishop's Stortford, Bishop's Castle and King's Lynn (among many others) but St Albans, St Andrews and St Helens.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] London Underground's Piccadilly line has the adjacent stations of Earl's Court in Earl's Court and Barons Court.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] These names were mainly fixed in form many years before grammatical rules were fully standardised.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] While Newcastle United play football at a stadium called St James' Park, and Exeter City at St James Park, London has a St James's Park (this whole area of London is named after the parish of St James's Church, Piccadilly).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Modern usage has been influenced by considerations of technological convenience including the economy of typewriter ribbons and films, and similar computer character "disallowance" which tend to ignore past standards.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Practice in the United Kingdom and Canada is not so uniform.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Style guides typically advise consulting an official source for the standard form of the name (as one would do if uncertain about other aspects of the spelling of the name); some tend towards greater prescriptiveness, for or against such an apostrophe.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] As the case of *womens* shows, it is not possible to analyze these forms simply as non-possessive plurals, since *women* is the only correct plural form of *woman*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Where a business name is based on a family name it should in theory take an apostrophe, but many leave it out (contrast *Sainsbury's* with *Harrods*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In recent times there has been an increasing tendency to drop the apostrophe.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Names based on a first name are more likely to take an apostrophe, but this is not always the case.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some business names may inadvertently spell a different name if the name with an ⟨s⟩ at the end is also a name, such as Parson.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] A spokesperson for Barclays PLC stated, "It has just disappeared over the years.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Following an evolution in usage in the 20th century, today "the apostrophe of plurality continues in at least five areas": abbreviations, letters of the alphabet/small words, numbers, family names, and in non-standard use.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For abbreviations, including acronyms, the use of *s* without an apostrophe is now more common than its use with an apostrophe.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Most modern style guides disparage the use of apostrophes in all plural abbreviations.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some references continue to condone their use, or even recommend their use in some abbreviations.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For example, *The Canadian Style* states "Add an apostrophe and *s* to form the plural of abbreviations containing more than one period", so *G.M.'s* is preferred to *G.M.s*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The *Oxford Companion to the English Language* condones *V.I.P.'s*, *VIP's*, and *VIPs* equally.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For single lowercase letters, pluralization with *'s* is usual.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Many guides recommend apostrophes whether the single letters are lowercase (as in "minding your p's and q's") or uppercase (as in "A's and S's").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] *The Chicago Manual of Style* recommends the apostrophe of plurality only for lowercase letters.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Sometimes, adding just *s* rather than *'s* may leave meaning ambiguous or presentation inelegant; however, an apostrophe is not always the preferred solution.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] APA style requires the use of italics instead of an apostrophe: *p*s, *n*s, etc.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In the phrase *dos and don'ts*, most modern style guides disparage spelling the first word as *do's*; however, there is a lack of consensus and certainly the use of an apostrophe continues, legitimately, in which "the apostrophe of plurality occurs in the first word but not the second".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The *Oxford Companion to the English Language* notes that "a plural *s* after a set of numbers is often preceded by an apostrophe, as in *3's and 4's*..., but many housestyles and individuals now favour *3s and 4s*".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Most style guides prefer the lack of apostrophe for groups of years (e.g.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] While many guides discourage using an apostrophe in all numbers/dates, many other guides *encourage* using an apostrophe for numbers or are divided on the issue; for example, the *Australian Government Style Manual* recommends "Binary code uses 0's and 1's" but recommends "the 2020s".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Still other guides take a laissez-faire approach.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For example, the University of Sussex's online guide notes regional variation in the use of apostrophes in dates, and slightly prefers *1's and 7's* over *1s and 7s* but condones both.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The apostrophe is very often used in plurals of symbols, for example "that page has too many &'s and #'s on it".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some style guides state that the apostrophe is unnecessary since there is no ambiguity but that some editors and teachers prefer this usage.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The addition of an *s* without an apostrophe may make the text difficult to read.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For many numbers and symbols, a useful alternative is to write out the numbers as words (e.g.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The vast majority of English references published from the late 20th century onwards disparage the use of apostrophes in family-name plurals, for example identifying *Joneses* as correct and *Jones's* as incorrect.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] As an exception, the *Oxford Companion to the English Language* (2018) reports that, in addition to *Joneses* etc., standard apostrophe usage does continue "in family names, especially if they end in *-s*, as in *keeping up with the Jones's*".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] See § Superfluous apostrophes ("greengrocers' apostrophes"), below.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Names that are not strictly native to English sometimes have an apostrophe substituted to represent other characters (see also As a mark of elision, below).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In transliterated foreign words, an apostrophe may be used to separate letters or syllables that otherwise would likely be interpreted incorrectly.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Furthermore, an apostrophe may be used to indicate a glottal stop in transliterations.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Rather than ʿ (modifier letter left half ring), the apostrophe is sometimes used to indicate a voiced pharyngeal fricative as it sounds and looks like the glottal stop to most English speakers.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Finally, in "scientific" transliteration of Cyrillic script, the apostrophe usually represents the soft sign ь, although in "ordinary" transliteration it is usually omitted.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Failure to observe standard use of the apostrophe is widespread and frequently criticised as incorrect, often generating heated debate.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The British founder of the Apostrophe Protection Society earned a 2001 Ig Nobel prize for "efforts to protect, promote and defend the differences between plural and possessive".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] A 2004 report by British examination board OCR stated that "the inaccurate use of the apostrophe is so widespread as to be almost universal".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] A 2008 survey found that nearly half of the UK adults polled were unable to use the apostrophe correctly.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Apostrophes used in a non-standard manner to form noun plurals are known as *greengrocers' apostrophes* or *grocer's apostrophes*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] They are sometimes humorously called *greengrocers apostrophe's*, *rogue apostrophes*, or *idiot's apostrophes* (a literal translation of the German word *Deppenapostroph*, which criticises the misapplication of apostrophes in Denglisch).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The practice, once common and acceptable (see *Historical development*), comes from the identical sound of the plural and possessive forms of most English nouns.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] It is often criticised as a form of hypercorrection coming from a widespread ignorance of the proper use of the apostrophe or of punctuation in general.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Lynne Truss, author of *Eats, Shoots & Leaves*, points out that before the 19th century it was standard orthography to use the apostrophe to form a plural of a foreign-sounding word that ended in a vowel (e.g., banana's, folio's, logo's, quarto's, pasta's, ouzo's) to clarify pronunciation.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Truss says this usage is no longer considered proper in formal writing.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The term is believed to have been coined in the middle of the 20th century by a teacher of languages working in Liverpool, at a time when such mistakes were common in the handwritten signs and advertisements of greengrocers (e.g., *Apple's 1/- a pound, Orange's 1/6 a pound*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Some have argued that its use in mass communication by employees of well-known companies has led to the less literate assuming it to be standard and adopting the habit themselves.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The same use of apostrophe before noun plural -s forms is sometimes made by non-native speakers of English.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For example, in Dutch, the apostrophe is inserted before the *s* when pluralising most words ending in a vowel or *y* for example, *baby's* (English *babies*) and *radio's* (English *radios*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] This often produces so-called "Dunglish" errors when carried over into English.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Hyperforeignism has been formalised in some pseudo-anglicisms.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] For example, the French word *pin's* (from English *pin*) is used (with the apostrophe in both singular and plural) for collectible lapel pins.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Similarly, there is an Andorran football club called FC Rànger's (after such British clubs as Rangers F.C.) and a Japanese dance group called Super Monkey's.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In the UK there is a tendency to drop apostrophes in many commonly used names such as St Annes, St Johns Lane, and so on.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] UK supermarket chain Tesco omits the mark where standard practice would require it.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Signs in Tesco advertise (among other items) "mens magazines", "girls toys", "kids books" and "womens shoes".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The United States Board on Geographic Names discourages the use of possessive apostrophes in geographic names although state agencies do not always conform; Vermont's official state website provides information concerning Camel's Hump State Forest.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The Geographical Names Board of New South Wales, Australia, excludes possessive apostrophes from place names, along with other punctuation.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] George Bernard Shaw, a proponent of English spelling reform on phonetic principles, argued that the apostrophe was mostly redundant.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] He did not use it for spelling *cant*, *hes*, etc., in many of his writings; however, he allowed *I'm* and *it's*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Hubert Selby Jr. used a slash instead of an apostrophe mark for contractions and did not use an apostrophe at all for possessives.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Lewis Carroll made greater use of apostrophes, and frequently used *sha'n't*, with an apostrophe in place of the elided *ll* as well as the more usual *o*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] These authors' usages have not become widespread.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The British pop group Hear'Say famously made unconventional use of an apostrophe in its name.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Truss comments that "the naming of Hear'Say in 2001 was ... a significant milestone on the road to punctuation anarchy".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Over the years, the use of apostrophes has been criticised.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] George Bernard Shaw called them "uncouth bacilli", referring to the apostrophe-like shape of many bacteria.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The author and language commentator Anu Garg has called for the abolition of the apostrophe, stating "Some day this world would be free of metastatic cancers, narcissistic con men, and the apostrophe".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In his book *American Speech*, linguist Steven Byington stated of the apostrophe that "the language would be none the worse for its abolition".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Adrian Room, in his *English Journal* article "Axing the Apostrophe", argued that apostrophes are unnecessary, and context will resolve any ambiguity.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In a letter to the *English Journal*, Peter Brodie stated that apostrophes are "largely decorative ... [and] rarely clarify meaning".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Wells, emeritus professor of phonetics at University College London, says the apostrophe is "a waste of time".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] The Apostrophe Protection Society, founded by retired journalist John Richards in 2001, closed in 2019, after a period of 18 years of campaigning for its preservation and correct usage.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] Closing the association, Richards, then aged 96, said that "We, and our many supporters worldwide, have done our best but the ignorance and laziness present in modern times have won!".
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p01] In a *Chronicle of Higher Education* blog, Geoffrey Pullum proposed that the apostrophe be considered the 27th letter of the alphabet, arguing that it is not a form of punctuation.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In many languages, especially European languages, the apostrophe is used to indicate the elision of one or more sounds, as in English.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] The apostrophe represents sounds resembling the glottal stop in the Turkic languages and in some romanizations of Semitic languages, including Arabic and Hebrew.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In that case, the letter *'ayn* (Arabic ع and Hebrew ע) is correspondingly transliterated with the opening single quotation mark.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Some languages use the apostrophe to separate the root of a word and its affixes, especially if the root is foreign and unassimilated.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] The shape of the apostrophe originated in manuscript writing, as a point with a downwards tail curving clockwise.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] This is the form of the modern **punctuation apostrophe** (’), (which is also known informally as the **typeset apostrophe**, the **typographic apostrophe** or the **curly apostrophe**) and of the right single quotation mark.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Later sans-serif typefaces had stylised apostrophes with a more geometric or simplified form, but usually retaining the same directional bias as a closing quotation mark.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] This is known as the **typewriter apostrophe** or **vertical apostrophe**.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] The same convention was adopted for double quotation marks (").
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Both simplifications carried over to computer keyboards and the ASCII character set.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Formally, the symbol used to represent a foot of length, depth, or height, is ′ (prime) and that for the inch is ″ (double prime).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] (Thus, for example, the notation 5′ 7″ signifies 5 feet and 7 inches).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Similarly, the prime symbol is the formal representation of a minute of arc (1/60 of a degree in geometry and geomatics), and double prime represents a second of arc (for example, 17°54′32″ represents 17 degrees 54 minutes and 32 seconds).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Similarly in mathematics, the prime is generally used to generate more variable names for similar things without resorting to subscripts, with *x′* generally meaning something related to (or derived from) *x*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Because of the very close similarity of the typewriter apostrophe and typewriter double quote to prime and double prime, substitution in informal contexts is ubiquitous, but using the typewriter characters is deprecated in contexts where proper typography is important.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Using the typewriter characters also risks having an automatic process "correct" them into punctuation-style apostrophes and quotation marks, which are less similar to the intended symbols.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In modern computing practice, Unicode is the standard and default method for character encoding; however, Unicode itself and many legacy applications have echoes of earlier practices.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Furthermore, the limited character set provided by computer keyboards has also required practical and pragmatic adjustments.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] The typewriter apostrophe, ', was inherited by computer keyboards, and is the only apostrophe character available in the (7-bit) ASCII character encoding, at code value 0x27 (39).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In ASCII, it may be used to represent any of left single quotation mark, right single quotation mark, apostrophe, vertical line or prime (punctuation marks), or an acute accent (modifier letters).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In Unicode, which is a superset of ASCII, it is encoded as U+0027 ' APOSTROPHE.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Many earlier (pre-1985) computer displays and printers rendered the ASCII apostrophe as a punctuation apostrophe, and rendered the backtick (freestanding grave accent symbol, `, 0x60, 96) as a matching left single quotation mark.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] This allowed a more "typeset" appearance of text: ``I can't'' would appear as ``I can´t´´ on these systems.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] This can still be seen in many documents prepared at that time, and is still used in the TeX typesetting system to create typographic quotes.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Support for the punctuation apostrophe ( ’ ) was introduced in several 8-bit character encodings, such as the original Apple Macintosh operating system's Mac Roman character set (in 1984), and later in the CP1252 encoding of Microsoft Windows.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Both sets also used this code point for a closing single quote.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] There is no such character in ISO 8859-1.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] The Microsoft Windows code page CP1252 (sometimes incorrectly called *ANSI* or *ISO-Latin*) contains the punctuation apostrophe at 0x92.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Due to "smart quotes" in Microsoft software converting the ASCII apostrophe to this value, other software makers have been effectively forced to adopt this as a *de facto* convention.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] For instance, the HTML5 standard specifies that this value is interpreted as this character from CP1252.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Some earlier non-Microsoft browsers would display a '?' for this and make web pages composed with Microsoft software somewhat hard to read.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In Unicode, which practically all vendors have adopted, this apostrophe is encoded as U+2019 ’ RIGHT SINGLE QUOTATION MARK.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] The canonical name reflects the primary usage; its further use as the preferred form for an apostrophe is recorded in the database.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Although ubiquitous in typeset material, the punctuation apostrophe (’) is rather difficult to enter on a computer, since it does not have its own key on most types of consumer keyboard.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Outside the world of professional typesetting and graphic design, most people use the typewriter apostrophe (').
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Because typewriter apostrophes are now often automatically converted to punctuation apostrophes by word processing and similar software, the punctuation apostrophe routinely appears in documents produced by non-professionals (albeit sometimes incorrectly—see § Smart Quotes below).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] XML (and hence XHTML) defines an `&apos;` character entity reference for the ASCII typewriter apostrophe.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] This entity reference is officially supported in HTML since HTML 5.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] To make punctuation apostrophes easier to enter, word processing and publishing software often convert typewriter apostrophes to punctuation apostrophes during text entry (at the same time converting opening and closing single and double quotes to their standard left-handed or right-handed forms).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] A similar facility may be offered on web servers after submitting text in a form field, e.g. on weblogs or free encyclopedias.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] This is known as the *smart quotes* feature; apostrophes and quotation marks that are not automatically altered by computer programs are known as *dumb quotes*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Smart quotes features often incorrectly convert a leading apostrophe to an opening quotation mark (e.g., in abbreviations of years: *‘29* rather than the correct *’29* for the years *1929* or *2029* (depending on context); or *‘twas* instead of *’twas* as the archaic abbreviation of *it was*).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Smart quote features also often fail to recognise situations when a prime rather than an apostrophe is needed; for example, incorrectly rendering the latitude 49° 53′ 08″ as 49° 53’ 08”.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In Microsoft Word, it is possible to turn smart quotes off (in some versions, by navigating through *Tools*, *AutoCorrect*, *AutoFormat as you type*, and then unchecking the appropriate option).
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Alternatively, typing Control-Z (for *Undo*) immediately after entering the apostrophe will convert it back to a typewriter apostrophe.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In Microsoft Word for Windows, holding down the Control key while typing two apostrophes will produce a single punctuation apostrophe.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Some programming languages, like Pascal, use the ASCII apostrophe to delimit string literals.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In many languages, including JavaScript, ECMAScript, and Python, either the apostrophe or the double quote may be used, allowing string literals to contain the other character (but not to contain both without using an escape character), e.g.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Strings delimited with apostrophes are often called *single quoted*.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] Some languages, such as Perl, PHP, and many shell languages, treat single quoted strings as "raw" strings, while double quoted strings have expressions (such as `"$variable"`) replaced with their values when interpreted.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] The C programming language (and many derived languages like C++, Java, C#, and Scala) uses apostrophes to delimit a character literal.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In these languages a character is a different object than a one-letter string.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In C++, since C++14, apostrophes can be included as optional digit separators in numeric literals.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In Visual Basic (and earlier Microsoft BASIC dialects such as QuickBASIC) an apostrophe is used to denote the start of a comment.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In the Lisp family of programming languages, an apostrophe is shorthand for the `quote` operator.
[src:apostrophe/apostrophe-p02] In Rust, in addition to being used to delimit a character literal, an apostrophe can start an explicit lifetime.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:apostrophe/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:apostrophe/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city's official name is a contraction of the (archaic) Dutch *des Hertogen bosch* ('the forest of the duke').
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The duke in question was Henry I, Duke of Brabant, whose family had owned a large estate at nearby Orthen for at least four centuries.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] He founded a new town located on some forested dunes in the middle of a marsh.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] At age 26, he granted 's-Hertogenbosch city rights and the corresponding trade privileges in 1185.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This is the traditional date given by later chroniclers; the first mention in contemporaneous sources is 1196.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] His reason for founding the city was to protect his own interests against encroachment from Gelre and Holland; from its first days, he conceived of the city as a fortress.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It was destroyed in 1203 in a joint expedition of Gelre and Holland, but was soon rebuilt.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Some remnants of the original city walls remain.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In the late 14th century, a much larger wall was erected to protect the greatly expanded settled area.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Artificial waterways were dug to serve as a city moat, through which the rivers Dommel and Aa were diverted.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch became the birthplace and home of northern Renaissance painter Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1520, the city flourished, becoming the second largest population centre in the territory of the present Netherlands, after Utrecht.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city was also a center of music, and composers, such as Jheronimus Clibano, received their training at its churches.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Others held positions there: Matthaeus Pipelare was musical director at the Confraternity of Our Lady; and renowned Habsburg copyist and composer Pierre Alamire did much of his work at 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The wars of the Reformation changed the course of the city's history.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] During the Eighty Years' War, the city took the side of the Habsburg (Catholic) authorities and thwarted a Calvinist coup.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It was besieged several times by Prince Maurice of Orange, stadtholder of most of the Dutch Republic, who wanted to bring 's-Hertogenbosch under the rule of the rebel United Provinces.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city was successfully defended against Prince Maurice in 1601 and again in 1603, but it eventually fell in the 1629 siege led by his brother Frederick Henry.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In the years of Truce, before the renewed fighting after 1618, the fortifications were greatly expanded.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The surrounding marshes made a siege of the conventional type impossible, and the fortress, deemed impregnable, was nicknamed *moerasdraak*, or the Swamp Dragon.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The town was nevertheless finally conquered by Frederik Hendrik of Orange in 1629 in a typically Dutch stratagem: he diverted the rivers Dommel and Aa, created a polder by constructing a forty-kilometre (25 mile) dyke and then pumped out the water by mills.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] After a siege of three months, the city had to surrender—an enormous blow to Habsburg geo-political strategy during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This surrender cut the town off from the rest of the duchy and the area was treated by the Republic as an occupation zone without political liberties (see also Generality Lands).
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] After the Peace of Westphalia, the fortifications were again expanded.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 1672, the Dutch *rampjaar*, the city held against the army of Louis XIV of France.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 1794 French revolutionary troops under the command of Charles Pichegru attacked the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It was only weakly defended, and fell after a short siege.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Pichegru then crossed the rivers and put an end to the Dutch Republic.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Under the new Batavian Republic, established in 1795, both Catholics and *Brabanders* at last gained equal rights.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] From 1806, the city became part of the Kingdom of Holland and from 1810, it was incorporated into the First French Empire.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It was captured by the Prussians in 1814.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The next year, 1815, when the United Kingdom of the Netherlands was established, it became the capital of North Brabant.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Many newer and more modern fortresses were created in the vicinity of the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] A new canal was built, the 'Zuid-Willemsvaart', which gave the city an economic impulse.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1878, it was forbidden to build outside the ramparts.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] That led to overcrowding and the highest infant mortality in the kingdom.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] At the end of the 19th century, the very conservative city government prevented industrial investment to avoid an increase in the number of workers and the establishment of educational institutions: students were regarded as disorderly.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] As a result, the relative importance of the city diminished.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] One of the few official Nazi concentration camp complexes in Western Europe outside Germany and Austria was named after 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It operated from January 1943, to September 1944 and was known to the Germans as Herzogenbusch (see List of subcamps of Herzogenbusch).
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] About 30,000 inmates were interned in the complex during this time, of whom about 12,000 were Jews.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In the Netherlands, this camp is known as 'Kamp Vught', because the concentration camp was actually located at a heath near Vught, a village a few kilometres south of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city was occupied by German forces during World War II from 1940 to 1944.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The railway station was bombed by planes of the Royal Air Force on 16 September 1944.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city was liberated between 24 and 27 October 1944 during Operation Pheasant by British soldiers of Major-General Robert Knox Ross's 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division following the victory of the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment, of 158th Infantry Brigade over the enemy on 23–24 October.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] After the war, 's-Hertogenbosch was modernized, like many other cities in the Netherlands.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It was possible that it was only the geography that shielded the old town from rigorous reconstruction in those early years.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Just in time, the pendulum swung back to protecting the history of the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 1956, the council wanted to demolish the Moriaan, the oldest brick building in the Netherlands, to give traffic better access to the market square.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The permit was refused by the government and instead the building was restored, starting in 1963.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Later, city councils became much more aware of the value of historic buildings and from about the turn of the millennium, the historic fortifications are also given much attention by the authorities.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The population centres in the municipality are: Bokhoven, Crevecoeur, Deuteren (former village), Dieskant, Empel, Engelen, Gewande, 's-Hertogenbosch, Hintham, Kruisstraat, Maliskamp, Meerwijk, Orthen (former village), Oud-Empel, and Rosmalen.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Climate in this area has mild differences between highs and lows, and there is adequate rainfall year-round.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Köppen Climate Classification subtype for this climate is "Cfb" (Marine West Coast Climate/Oceanic climate).
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city of 's-Hertogenbosch has become a center of industry, education, administration and culture.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is currently the fourth city of North Brabant.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is home to many national and international businesses such as Heineken, Epic, Tyco International, SAP and many others.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Jeroen Bosch Hospital is the biggest employer in the area, with over 4,000 employees.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] There are also over 350 restaurants, pubs and cafés to be found in the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is also home to the European Ceramic Work Centre.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This is a juried international ceramic residency where they invite artists, designers and architects from around to the world to explore the medium of Ceramics.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This program was initially started in 1991 and continues to this day.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city has its own food speciality, the Bossche Bol—effectively a giant profiterole, somewhat larger than a tennis ball, which is filled with whipped cream and coated with chocolate.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The spoken language is Maaslands (the variant spoken in 's-Hertogenbosch is called *Bosch* which is placed among the Central North Brabantian dialects, although other classification systems also describe it as East Brabantian), which is very similar to colloquial Dutch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] De Toonzaal is a music venue for chamber music, improvised music, and experimental music.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] For popular music there is the venue W2 (or Willem II).
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Noordbrabants Museum is a provincial museum with an overview of works that Vincent van Gogh made in Brabant.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Design Museum Den Bosch is a modern art museum.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Bosch Art Center, is dedicated to the work of Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Other museums include the Swan Brothers' House and Museum Slager.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Also the National (Dutch) Carnavalsmuseum Oeteldonks gemintemuzejum is located in the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In the near future a new museum will be opened about the fortresses of the town and in general in Europe.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The house where the famous painter Hieronymus produced his paintings can be visited on the market square.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has a strong carnival tradition.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In its current form the story and symbolism dates from 1881 to 1883.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In these years some citizens created the legend of "Oeteldonk", whereby the city was renamed to Oeteldonk for the three day carnival.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] "Donk" is a reference to a dry place in the marsh.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The frog is widely used as a symbol during the 's-Hertogenbosch Carnival.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is also a symbol of the Oeteldonk marsh.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It was also a remark aimed at Bishop Godschalk from Den Dungen, where 'Van den Oetelaar' was a common family name.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] He had wanted to forbid the traditional festivities of Shrove Tuesday that often led to excesses.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Oeteldonk is a village and therefore every inhabitant is a farmer or a '*durske*' (a girl or young woman), eliminating class differences.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The village is headed by the Mayor "Peer vaan den Muggenheuvel tot den Bobberd".
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Each year the mayor of 's-Hertogenbosch hands over his authority to the Mayor of Oeteldonk.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] On Sunday at 11:11 AM the Mayor of Oeteldonk then receives Prince Carnaval "Prince Amadeiro XXVI" at Oeteldonk central station.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] From there a parade of all carnival clubs escorts the company to the town hall.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The citizens of 's-Hertogenbosch wear traditional outfits throughout these days.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] A so-called *boerenkiel* is worn and every year patches are designed according to that years theme which can then be stitched onto the outfit.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The *boerenkiel* is often combined with a traditional farmers bandana and a long scarf in the colors of Oeteldonk.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The tradition of the Boerenkiel and / or Bandana is very different from the carnival traditions in the rest of the Netherlands.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Other aspects like the parade, the temporary name and the temporary flag (for Oeteldonk red, white and yellow) are very similar.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch was founded as a fortified city and that heritage can still be seen today.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] After World War II, plans were made to modernise the old city, by filling in the canals, removing or modifying some ramparts and redeveloping historic neighbourhoods.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Before these plans could come to effect, the central government declared the city a protected townscape.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Most historic elements have been preserved.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In contrast to cities like Rotterdam, 's-Hertogenbosch also survived the Second World War relatively unscathed.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Much of its historic heritage remains intact, and today there are always renovations going on in the city to preserve the many old buildings, fortifications, churches and statues for later generations.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city center has a cosy atmosphere because of the almost continuous ramparts that still surround it.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It has been molded by the multiple rivers that convene on 's-Hertogenbosch, giving the center its strange street plan so different from the usual grid plan where streets meet at right angles.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The center is dominated by Saint John's Cathedral (*Sint-Janskathedraal* in Dutch), which dates from c.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 1220 and is best known for its Brabantine Gothic design and the many sculptures of craftsmen that are sitting on almost every arc and rim along the outside of the cathedral.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 2010 an extensive restoration was completed, undoing the damage of many years of wear-and-tear and acid rain.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] On the central square is the oldest remaining brick house of the Netherlands, 'de Moriaan', which was built at the beginning of the 13th century.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In the 1960s, de Moriaan was renovated to its former glory based on a famous 16th-century Dutch painting called 'De Lakenmarkt van 's-Hertogenbosch' ('The fabric market of 's-Hertogenbosch').
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The town hall is an original 14th-century Gothic building.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] After the town was conquered by the Dutch Republic in 1629, it received a new facade in the style of Dutch Baroque architecture.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It showcased the authority of the new masters, just like the new town hall in Maastricht would.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Hidden below the old city is a canal network called the Binnendieze, which once spanned 22 km (14 mi).
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It started out as a regular river, the Dommel, running through the city in medieval times.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Due to a lack of space in the city, people started building their houses and roads over the river.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Later, the Binnendieze functioned as a sewer and fell into disrepair.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In recent decades, the remaining sixth part of the old waterway system has been renovated, and it is possible to take several guided subterranean boat trips through it.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has an extensive and almost complete fifteenth-to-seventeenth-century city fortification.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It was made to profit from the city's strong defensive position, lying on a sandy hill in the center of a large swamp fed by many rivers.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This also caused the main ramparts to be preserved, because they were crucial in keeping out the water.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 2004 the city was awarded the title *European Fortress City of the year*.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In the years that followed it restored many of the city defenses to much of their old glory.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Apart from small sections of medieval walls, the main structure of the fortification is a late-medieval (fifteenth-century) wall.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The upper sections were removed when cannon became more powerful, and polygonal bastions were added, some after the conquest by the republic.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Most of these have not been restored to their original height, but do maintain their brick walls.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The citadel in the north west of the city does retain its original height.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Around the city itself many other fortresses can still be seen.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In the north east of the old city, the hexagonal gunpowder magazine, called *Kruithuis* is located close to the citadel.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is one of only a handful that still exist in the Netherlands, and was built when the city was still part of the Spanish Netherlands.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is planned to become the museum of fortress 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] One of the bastions of the fortress now houses the mini museum Bastionder.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It has been dug out in a bastion of the south side.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] On the inside it shows a unique wrought iron cannon, and an older bastion that was walled in by the current one.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] On the south side of the city, the city center and walls still border the Bossche Broek, an old polder that could never be made dry.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 1995 the dyke of the Dommel broke and an enormous amount of water entered the polder.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It also flooded and blocked the main Dutch highway A2.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In order to prevent this in the future, the area was rearranged to store excess water in case of emergencies.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 2006 the area had been furnished with higher dikes and locks that allowed a controlled flooding of the polder and some adjacent areas in case of emergency.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Bossche Broek is now a 22-hectare (54-acre) nature reserve, that stretches all the way to Vught.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is connected to the Moerputten and Vlijmens Ven, with which it forms a Natura 2000 area.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Rare species in the area are the scarce large blue and the European weather loach.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Moerputten sports the Moerputten Bridge, a 600-metre (650 yard) long nineteenth century railway bridge and engineering feat.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] What is unique about the area is its close proximity to the city center.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city is also the location of the *Bolwoningen* complex, an array of fifty experimental spherical houses designed by Dries Kreijkamp.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Lutheran Church, 's-Hertogenbosch is no longer used as a church.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city has one professional football club, FC Den Bosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is the 1967 successor of the professional branches of BVV (Bossche Voetbal Vereniging) and Wilhelmina.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Both of them still exist as amateur football clubs.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] As a successor of BVV FC Den Bosch can claim the national championship of 1948.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This championship led to the construction of stadium De Vliert, which at one time had a capacity of 30,000.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Due to the less successful years that followed, the capacity is now only 8,500 visitors.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] FC Den Bosch was the first club of Dutch international player Ruud van Nistelrooy.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is more successful in field hockey.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The women's team in particular is a dominant force in the Dutch field hockey competition.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The professional basketball club Heroes Den Bosch is also very successful.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The city's rugby club is called The Dukes and dates from 1974.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is located at a very scenic location at the foot of the city walls.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Because of the limited space, the club plays on artificial turf and part of the accommodation is subterranean.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It became the national rugby champion in 2008.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] As regards events the city is host to the Rosmalen Grass Court Championships, a combined ATP Tour and WTA Tour grass court tennis event played two weeks before the Wimbledon Championships.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The World Archery Championships and World Para Archery Championship were held here in June 2019.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] During these combined World Championships two separate venues were used: the Parade and the rugby fields of The Dukes.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] All finals took place in the arena at the Parade.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Parade is a historic square surrounded by high trees, situated at the foot of the nearly seven-hundred-year-old Saint John's Cathedral in the attractive center of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Zuid-Willemsvaart runs from the Meuse just north of the city towards Maastricht via Helmond and Weert.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 's-Hertogenbosch it runs through the city proper, south east from where a bastion has been cut off from the citadel.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Because of this route it was impossible to widen it further than for ships of CEMT class II.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Therefore, the Máxima Canal of 8 km (5 miles) was dug just east of the city, creating a shortcut from the canal to the Meuse suitable for ships of CEMT class IV.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] On the remaining part of the Zuid-Willemsvaart west of the city is the industrial harbor of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is situated on the busy A2 motorway, the most important north–south connection of the Netherlands.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This connection was established with the opening of the Dieze Bridge in 1942.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] From 1961 the Utrecht-'s-Hertogenbosch section was 2 times 2 lanes.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 1970 the A2 was rerouted to the east of the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 1989 it finally became a controlled-access highway.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 1996 the section between 's-Hertogenbosch and Eindhoven became a controlled-access highway.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The situation in Maastricht was only solved in 2016, when the Koning Willem-Alexandertunnel was opened.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] On the east–west axis 's-Hertogenbosch is on the A59 motorway.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The A65 motorway between 's-Hertogenbosch and Tilburg is a regional highway, but is not completely access-controlled.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is on the Utrecht–Boxtel part of the railway stretch between Amsterdam and the Dutch industrial/tech center near Eindhoven.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] As a consequence north–south trains depart every ten minutes.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] On the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway trains run on a more modest schedule.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is also a major station for Arriva buslines that serve the city and most of its suburbs.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Other stations within the limits of the municipality are 's-Hertogenbosch Oost railway station and Rosmalen railway station.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Vught railway station is actually closer to the city center than that in Rosmalen.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has attempted to adapt to the growing popularity of the bicycle in Dutch cities.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] A reasonable amount of bike paths has so far been constructed in the town.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In 2011, the city was chosen as *Fietsstad 2011*—the top bike city of the Netherlands for 2011.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] This is a big achievement for a city where bicycle use is lower than in the rest of the Netherlands".
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has multiple vocational universities called *Hogeschool* in Dutch.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The HAS Hogeschool of about 3,500 students is focused on agricultural and food technology.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Avans Hogeschool is located in 's-Hertogenbosch and two nearby cities.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Joost is an art academy that is now part of Avans and dates back to 1812.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Fontys Hogeschool also offers some education in the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Academy of Data Science (JADS), located at the Mariënburg Campus in the center of 's-Hertogenbosch, and provides a number of data science programs at graduate (MSc) and post-graduate level (PhD).
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is a department of the Eindhoven University of Technology and Tilburg University.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] In secondary education the City Gymnasium is a gymnasium (school) that originated from the Latin school of the city.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is comparable to a grammar school and can trace its origin back 1274.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The same type of education and all other types of secondary education are offered by a number of large institutes.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Roman Catholicism is the dominant religion in 's-Hertogenbosch, with somewhat more than 40% of the population counting themselves as belonging to it.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Even so, attendance at mass is significantly lower than 40%.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Three churches in the city center are still in use by the Catholic church: Saint John's Cathedral, Saint Catherine and the Monastery Church of the Franciscans nearby the railway station.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] Smaller churches in use by the Roman Catholic church are: Saint Anne's Church in Hintham, Saint Landoline Church in Empel, Saint Willibrord Church in Maaspoort, Saint Lambert Church (Rosmalen), etc.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Protestant religion has seen its share of believers in the city fall from 20% to about 4%.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Eastern Orthodox Church is a new church in town.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] It is based at Saint Catherine's Church where Catholic worship services have been held again since 2021.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Arrahma Mosque has been built by the Moroccan community.
[src:apostrophe/s-hertogenbosch] The Turkish community has the Orhan Gazi Mosque.
